Last year I had just ended a 7 year relationship with my loving boyfriend, as I realized we were not compatible. The breakup was devastating amp; thought I #8217;d never emotionally survive. In the year that passed, I #8217;ve turned 30, gotten a promotion, amp; head to Miami in a week for a girls #8217; trip. I am happy.

WRITING.TEXT: I #8217;m sorry to hear about your divorce. And you will! I #8217;m surprised to be sitting here because I #8217;m in the exact spot I was a year ago when I was sobbing my eyes out, pretty much certain I would never be okay again. It #8217;s crazy what a year can do. I still have my moments where I miss him dearly (more so, our incredible bond, memories and friendship that we had while we were together) but I do not regret my choice and know that it was for the absolute best. I hope your year is as reflective as mine was. #128151;

Stay strong and remember that even though the hardest part is upon you, you WILL get through this. #128153;

Stay strong and stay busy. What you #8217;re feeling right now will soon be a distant memory. It will still hurt at times but you #8217;ll feel a new layer of strength. You #8217;ve got this. #128153;

If it #8217;s meant to, it will! I #8217;m a year out and there are times I #8217;m triggered by a memory we had together and it can feel temporarily debilitating. However, something that helped me when I was going back amp; forth on whether or not to end things was to just ask myself #8220;does this feel right, and can I do this forever? #8221; Before my head or my heart could answer, my gut would always tell me the truth.

We have no plans! Please send me things to do! We #8217;re all 30, enjoy the club scene on occasion but also mostly laid back and don #8217;t mind margaritas and beers in a laid back outdoor bar. We #8217;re staying in the middle of south beach and also are all about day drinking lol so I #8217;d love to hear of any fun spots!

It was so much back amp; forth for me, it was unreal. I actually found myself searching #8220;should I break up with my boyfriend of 7 years #8221; articles to see if other women had been through the same thing. (which I don #8217;t recommend, because every article is basically saying #8216;if you have a nice guy, don #8217;t let him go! #8217;) I didn #8217;t realize then that people who are in happy, fulfilling relationships aren #8217;t taking time to search the Internet for advice on whether or not to break up. In the hopes of not making this too long, we were together from ages 22-29, and in that time we grew a LOT. I felt like I had a huge list of things I wanted to see/accomplish, and wanted to live as full a life as I could, while he became more focused on laying down roots, settling into life and eventually having a family. We had always been very different people, but it seemed like we were slowly losing our common ground. Also, I found myself going on more adventures and traveling more with my friends, (and he was always very supportive of this but had no interest in coming along) and when I #8217;d get back I #8217;d tell him a million stories of funny memories and things that happened. I used to love doing that and he would always listen intently and we #8217;d laugh together, but there was one point when I realized #8220;hey...I don #8217;t want to come home and tell him all the cool stuff I did, I want him to WANT to do this cool stuff with me. #8221; (Over the years we had many talks and went back and forth about trying to do things that the other enjoyed, but at the end of the day, being very different in terms of interests and what we wanted out of life was something that became difficult to get around and ignore.) I think it really ended with me having to decide who I loved more, him or myself. And while it was extremely difficult and something I never want to go through again, I chose myself. Just remember: if you #8217;re going back and forth on it, that may be your sign. Even though I don #8217;t recommend searching the Internet cause you #8217;ll just find a bunch of stories of how #8220;leaving the nice guy is a terrible idea #8221;, [this article ](https://www.manrepeller.com/2017/03/should-i-break-up-with-my-boyfriend.html) was the only one I found that mirrored exactly what I was going through. I read it several times (and still go back to read it from time to time). It has helped a lot. Good luck. #128151;

WRITING.TEXT: It was about 6 degrees every day, and dropped below 0 at night!
I #8217;d love to go during summer, just to see the differences. The winter was pretty magical, though.
We went specifically for the winter carnival, but actually ended up doing more sight seeing than participating! It was still such a fun time.

It depends how used to cold temps you are...I #8217;m from Maine so I was pretty prepared, although I won #8217;t lie, at night it got absolutely freezing. As long as you #8217;re bundled up (I wore lots of layers and water proof boots, fleece leggings and wool socks) you #8217;ll be fine to walk around. We arrived during a blizzard which made things even more picturesque, despite the fact that it was so cold. I think Christmas would be perfect! It will be busy, but everything will be covered in snow and sparkling with lights. We spent the week sight-seeing by day, and dipping in and out of little cafes and pubs for warm beverages at night.

WRITING.TITLE: I #8217;m pretty terrible at cooking but I am proud of this one...gnocchi with bacon cream sauce!
Gnocchi with bacon cream sauce...I #8217;m still working on my cooking skills but I #8217;m proud of this one.

WRITING.TEXT: The gnocchi isn #8217;t. #128584; but everything else is!

Ingredients: 1 lb gnocchi Water enough to fill a large pot 3/4 full 4 strips smoked bacon chopped 2 cloves garlic pressed or minced 2 egg yolks beaten well 1/4 cup milk or cream 1/4 cup freshly grated parmesan cheese 1/4 cup chicken broth 1/2 tbsp cornstarch Salt and pepper to taste Chopped parsley and more parmesan to garnish Directions: 1. Bring water, salted heavily, to a boil in a large pot. 2. In a medium mixing bowl, mix together egg yolks, milk and cheese with a fork or whisk. Set aside. 3. In a large high sided saute pan over medium high heat, cook chopped bacon to desired crispness. At this point, you could remove or keep the rendered bacon fat, it's entirely up to you. Once done, turn heat to low and add garlic. Stir well, making sure garlic doesn't burn. ***4. Add gnocchi to the water and cook for 2-3 minutes, or as package describes. 5. While gnocchi is cooking, add the egg mixture to the bacon in the skillet (heat still on low, or turned off) and whisk well. In a small bowl, whisk the chicken broth into the cornstarch, then add to the sauce, whisking well to incorporate. 6. Drain gnocchi, then add to skillet and toss well with sauce. 7. Serve immediately with parsley and parmesan as garnish ***I actually had to use #8216;skillet gnocchi #8217; (it was all they had left at the store) so I cooked it in a separate fry pan and then added it to the mixture at the end!
